<paper id="1596546325"><title>Secure Commitment Against A Powerful Adversary</title><year>1992</year><authors><author org="MIT — Laboratory for Computer Science" id="1482108584">Rafail Ostrovsky</author><author org="Bell Communications Research#TAB#" id="2126319880">Ramarathnam Venkatesan</author><author org="(IBM Research)" id="2097786798">Moti Yung</author></authors><n_citation>17</n_citation><doc_type>Conference</doc_type><references><reference>340987026</reference><reference>1494965429</reference><reference>1496630551</reference><reference>1528588003</reference><reference>1600605837</reference><reference>1603973540</reference><reference>1679526205</reference><reference>1987667503</reference><reference>2012045293</reference><reference>2015826302</reference><reference>2016443801</reference><reference>2021320809</reference><reference>2023906228</reference><reference>2027528470</reference><reference>2032133054</reference><reference>2074876220</reference><reference>2082647621</reference><reference>2100008268</reference><reference>2134238617</reference><reference>2151433956</reference><reference>2153708829</reference><reference>2168957864</reference><reference>2293988196</reference></references><venue id="1178070762" type="C">Symposium on Theoretical Aspects of Computer Science</venue><doi>10.1007/3-540-55210-3_203</doi><keywords><keyword weight="0.56593">Cryptography</keyword><keyword weight="0.46668">Computer security</keyword><keyword weight="0.58607">Adversary model</keyword><keyword weight="0.45425">Computer science</keyword><keyword weight="0.50659">Information hiding</keyword><keyword weight="0.57249">Information-theoretic security</keyword><keyword weight="0.51354">Adversary</keyword><keyword weight="0.42754">Seven Basic Tools of Quality</keyword><keyword weight="0.57989">Secure two-party computation</keyword><keyword weight="0.57724">Oblivious transfer</keyword></keywords><publisher>Springer, Berlin, Heidelberg</publisher><abstract>Secure commitment is a primitive enabling information hiding, which is one of the most basic tools in cryptography. Specifically, it is a two-party partial-information game between a “committer” and a “receiver”, in which a secure envelope is first implemented and later opened. The committer has a bit in mind which he commits to by putting it in a “secure envelope”. The receiver cannot guess what the value is until the opening stage and the committer can not change his mind once committed.</abstract></paper>